face of the cerebral hemisphere","Supplies the lateral surface of the frontal lobe","Supplies the entire frontal lobe"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial surface of the cerebral hemisphere\u003C/strong\u003E is supplied by the anterior cerebral artery, which runs in the longitudinal fissure between the cerebral hemispheres. It provides blood to the medial portions of the frontal and parietal lobes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe anterior cerebral artery does not supply the temporal and parietal lobes only, as it supplies medial portions of frontal and parietal lobes, not the temporal lobe. The occipital lobe exclusively is supplied by the posterior cerebral artery, not the anterior cerebral artery. The lateral surface of the frontal lobe is primarily supplied by the middle cerebral artery rather than the anterior cerebral artery. Only the medial and superior portions of the frontal lobe are supplied by the anterior cerebral artery, while the lateral portions are supplied by the middle cerebral artery, so it does not supply the entire frontal lobe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the distribution of the cerebral arteries is crucial for interpreting the clinical effects of cerebrovascular events affecting different regions of the brain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The anterior cerebral artery supplies the medial surface of the cerebral hemisphere, including parts of the frontal and parietal lobes.","The middle cerebral artery supplies most of the lateral surface of the cerebral hemisphere.","Both anterior and middle cerebral arteries arise as terminal branches of the internal carotid artery."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98409"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18648"}},"stem